column1: Before 16 February 2018, will President Trump sign legislation that reduces the top marginal federal corporate tax rate?
column4: Yes, to a rate greater than 20% but less than 25%

column11: The top marginal federal corporate tax rate is currently 35% (Cornell Law, CNBC, Harvard Business Review). The date that any change to the marginal rate would take effect is immaterial to the resolution of this question. Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

I am updating my previous forecast on account of the news that John McCain is going back to Arizona and will not be voting on the tax bill this coming week. The GOP can afford to lose one vote now and still pass the bill, so I still believe that it is quite likely that it will pass. Additionally, it has been said that, if necessary, McCain will return to D.C. to vote on the bill. All that being said, I believe the bill is less likely to pass in light of this news.

Given that Senator Rubio and Senator Corker recently announced their support for the current tax bill--which sets the top marginal federal corporate tax rate at 21 percent-- it seems highly likely that President Trump will sign the current tax bill before the end of the year.

Current corporate tax rate in the Senate and the House versions are 20%. There are talks of increasing it to 21% and Pres. Trump did say that he's still OK with 22%. The House will vote on the motion of accepting the Senate version as-is on Monday (I'll have to double check it means today Dec 4 or Monday Dec 11). So here are the odds: The tax rate remains at 20% if: 1. (a) The House will accept the Senate version as-is to avoid conference [50%] AND (b) done it before the end of the year [80% chance since there is plenty of time and only involve the House] AND (c) President Trump has no objection [100%, he already voiced his support, as is] AND (d) President Trump signs it [98%]

As I see it, the uncertainty for this question is now less about *whether* tax reform will get passed and more about *when*... What more is left to be done? Presumably, there's enough to be done that the likelihood of "President Trump [signing] legislation" after Feb. 16 is more than zero...right? I could be persuaded to assign less than a 25% chance to this possibility and would appreciate any insight others have on timing.

The more I think about it, having the tax cut happen immediately will likely be more of a priority than keeping the rate at 20%. Republicans paint a picture of the corporate tax cut as essential for the country to grow and wages to increase, etc. etc and that this needs to happen immediately, etc. So it doesn't feed into their urgent narrative to then vote to delay it. Taking a bit of a defensive position on the rate. Republicans will need a lot of money in the reconciliation talks, and Trump unexpectedly signaled flexibility on the rate up to 22 percent. Moreover, the Senate version has the cut only from 2019, while the House has it from 2018. A 22 percent rate from 2018 could be a possible compromise.

Obviously, the GOP is hellbent on achieving some form of legislative victory before the 2018 campaign really kicks off. With that said, there's still some significant hurdles to overcome for the tax bill to be signed by Feb 16.

I don't expect the House to pass the Senate version of the bill and believe it goes to conference committee to negotiate the differences in the two bills. I don't see the House increasing the corporate tax rate but they may not want to delay it as the Senate version delays its implementation till 2019. The House version makes individual tax cuts permanent while they sunset in the Senate version. The House wants to repeal the estate tax entirely. Whatever the House decides to restore in their version costs money and increases the deficit.

With Republicans in charge at both ends of Pennsylvania Avenue, and in desperate need of a major legislative victory, I believe that a corporate tax cut is not a question of “If”, but of “when” and “how much”. Entirely possible Republican leadership would be willing to give some on the 20% level in order to compromise and make room in the bill for some restoration of individual tax breaks being eliminated in the first draft, even though the President has stated that the 20% level is non-negotiable for him. For legislators, 20% may just be the opening gambit. See articles linked below:

It's a great distraction, with the failing dotard at 39% approval they desperately need a win. I'm assuming theocrat pedo Roy Moore (or a GOP Senator) takes over Russian-stooge AG Jeff Sessions' Alabama seat.

This is a key issue for the GOP to show that the election to a majority in Congress would result in some legislative campaign promises being met. Obviously if Congress passes such a reduction Trump will sign it. The question is will Congress pass it. Politically they should and therefore there should be a bill for Trump to sign. Do Flake, Johnson, Crocker or MaCain really care anymore about the GOP agenda or do they care more about the GOP agenda? That is the question.

Some adjustment in this tax is a good idea and everybody knows it. If the Rs could bring themselves to detach such a proposal from the more wild-eyed bits of their current gibberish, it would probably pass fairly quickly and even with some D votes. Bundled in with the favourite fantasies of Speaker Jellyspine, President LIttlefingers, and Distinguished Majority Leader Yertle the Turtle, it will die an inglorious death.

Obviously, I'm not particularly confident this will happen. The tax reform is already a challenge, with the House and Senate having different priorities for the new tax bill. And with the inclusion of the ACA mandate repeal, this becomes even more challenging. Right now, neither bill would pass a "Byrd bath" in the Senate to ensure compliance with reconciliation procedures, which further complicates the process, especially if the Senate passes their version and it goes to conference.
